{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332893786/1930111401/0248.xml":{"full_text":"I\nREPAIRING I\nDone In ear store tty expert work- 1\nmen. All <>ur work rnarantred. 1\nTHE VALLEY FIRST FIRST IN THE VALLEY\u2014LEASED WIRE SERVICE OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\u2014(jT) I\n_ __ I i. _ m I\n\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014^\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014.\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014w\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014w in \u2014\u2014\u2014w\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u25a0\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u25a0\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014w\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014 |H\nTHIRTY-NINTH YEAR_NO. 133 BROWNSVILLE, TEXAS, FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 14, 193Q TEN PAGES TODAY 5c A i:<*- r I\n'-.-maj\nIN OUR\nVALLEY!\nL- B1 C. M HALL\nHOW ABOUT IT?\nNo one would invite either\nwar or business depression, but\nJrom them may come some new\njm'Miirations.\nV* \u2014President Hoover.\n\nToo many authors **:m to be\nindulging in a free-for-all race\nfor bigger and better im\nmortalitr.\n\u2014G K Chesterton\n\nI God must find the United\nStates a rather difficult country\nto please\n\u2014Lord Melchett.\n\nT suppose the dogmas of the\nchurch were slogans.\n\u2014Dean Inge.\n11TITH the election of Brownsville\nW navigation commissioners set for\nDecember 2, it has been found\nthat many in Brownsville have not\na clear conception of the situation\nwith reference to handling the port\nand other navigation projects.\n'Rie present commissioners hold\noffice by appointment, following\ntheir appointment state legislation\nwas enacted requiring that such\nofficials be elected by popular vote.\nThe time has now rolled around\nto comply with that new law and\nthe election date set. What remains\nis for the district voters, included\nin the advertised formal call, to give\na full vote of confidence to those\nundertaking this task foi the city.\n\nBROWNSVILLE has been fortun\nate in having had the represen\ntation she has had or this com\nmission. It is a big undertaking re\nquiring hours and days of time in\nW*ork for the community. There\n\u201cis no compensation and sometimes\nwhen certain obstacles are confront\ned the commissioners have some\nrights to feel that it Is a thankless\ntask. A big vote will make them\nfeel better for this work of helping\nbetter the community. Speed in\nthe project has been had through\nsome of the members being bankers\nand in a position to advance funds\nend save time which otherwise would\nrepresent a waste.\n\nIlfHEN the actual work on the port\nW will start cannot be definitely\npointed out. but Major Milo P.\nFox. government engineer on the\nmatter, in a recent visit here, re\nmarked that the best progress he has\never seen on such a big project is\nbeing made.\nFor the sake of time as well as\nother considerations the same men\nwho have served in the past should\ncertainly be re-elected.\n\nA FEW days ago the engineer of\nthis column broke out with a\nnoise of disappointed duck hunt\ners because of so much water. That\nvery night a neighbor sent over four\nducks \"just to show us how wrong\nwe were.\"\nAll right if that is the way to cor\nrect a wrong we hear the turkey\nseason is going to be simply terrible\nwhen it opens Sunday.\n\nAFTER living in the Valiev under\nsuch circumstances Animated\nAnnie says she believes the boot\nlegger is the one guy who has to\nwait until his ship comes in.\ni\nfwoHE folks may criticize our ethics,\nbut it gets such wonderful re\nsults. Ethics at times is flexible\nand rightly should be so.\nBut not to the extent of the man\nwho asked what in the world busi\nness ethics is. He was told that a\ndefinition could not be given for it,\nbut that it could be explained as fol\nlows:\nA man. came into a store owned\nbv two partners and purchased $8\nworth of goods from cne of the\npartners. He tendered e. ten dollar\nbil! in payment. On the wav to the\ncash register the store owner dis\ncovered that two ten dollar bills\nwere stuck together\n\"Now.\u2019 It was explained, \"the\nquestion of ethics was should that\nowner tell his partner about it?\u201d\n\nA LETTER from San Benito today\nsigned A reader' asks that at\ntention be called to Valley well\nfishers not tc permit the beauty of\nthe Valley to be maimed with sign\npests\nA clipping was enclosed calling at\ntention to the fact that while Europe\ndrives the billboards from her hills i\nand highways American landscapes\nare being made hideous.\nSigns and billboards constitute one\nform of advertising American man\nufacturers and restaurants, or what\nrot, are willing to ape each other\nin. In some localities it is coming\nto the point where the scenery of\nferds the autoists not a view of the\noutdoors, but only an opportunity to\ndecide which cigarette ad offers the\nprettiest girl, or the most effeminate\nlooking man. There must be ten\nthousand Last Chance\" filling sta\ntions signs, and so on and so forth,\nuntil the landscape begins to pre\n'ie apoearance of b*ing enclos\ni wall running the length of\n,hway. This extreme has not\n:o the Valley yet. but we want\nto keep it so that our orchards and\ngardens will be visible from the\nroadside.\n\nAT last Valley shippers are about\nto form an organization with\none object in \\iew that of stab\nilizing the price of Valiev fruits. At\na meeting last night in Harlingen\na committee was appointed to plan\nthe association\nWhen the Valley gets organized\nlike California with the growers\nworking hand in hand with the\nsh\u2019opers. the fruit quotations list\nwill not so much resemble fn-e $ai*\nenrds. and consumers win not bd\nmistaking our early grape fruit and\noranges for lemon*\nCOAST CROPS\nARE DAMAGED\nBY SNOWFALL\nCalifornia In Grip\nOf Winter; Sun\nShines On Rio\nSAN FRANCISCO. Nov. 14\u2014OPV\nSuow. wind and rain combined to\nday to give California and the Pa\ncific northwest sharp warning ol\nwinter's approach.\nBeginning of the weather distub\nance yesterday brought reports ol\ndamage to crops and small watei\ncraft.\nAt Monterrey a fishing boat waj\ntorn from its moorings and twe\nbarges loaded with sardines wer<\nswamped. Rain at Modesto dam\naged drying beans while ir. the Fres\nI r.o cotton district growers wen\ntroubled.\nSnowfall closed Tioga Pass and\nBig Oak Flats roads m Yosemite\nTuolumme Meadows near the sum\nmit of Tioga Pass were buried un\nder a foot of snow. Nine inches fell\nat Crane Flat.\nPortland, Oregon, experienced the\nfirst snow of the season, as did Salt\nLake City. Utah\nAt Dawson, Yukon Territory, tht\nlast open spaces of the Yukon rivei\nwere frozen o\\er. and the stream\nwas ice-covered from Lake Laber\nage, Y. T., to Norton Sound. Alaska\nRam in central and southern\nCalifornia put an abrupt end to\nh:gh temperatures and reduced tc\nncrmal the fire hazard.\nIn Montana a snowstorm swept\ndewn from the north driving tem\nperatures to below freezing. Fifty\nautomobiles, belonging chiefly to\ntcurists. were snowbound near Great\nFalls. There w^as a possibility drift\ning snow would impound the cars\nuntil next spring. Ten women oc\ncupants of the stalled automobiles\nwalked six miles through the drifts\nto shelter. A group of twelve men\nsought refuge in a cabin.\nA drop in temperature of 37 de\ngrees at Helena brought the mer\ncury to 14 above zero last night.\nAnaconda reported 13 above.\nRio Hondo Litttle\nDamaged by Rain\n<Special to The Herald.)\nRIO HONDO. Nov. 14\u2014After\nabout eight days of almost steady\nprecipitation the major portion of\nthe farmers in this locality are out\nin their fields in Boots, draining\ntheir fields, where It is practical.\nThe unusually heavy rains of\nthis Pall have held back citrus\nshipments here. Only six cars of\nfruit ha\\> been shipped out of this\ndistrict this year, some fruit how\never was trucked out to San An\ntonio and other markets. The\ntomato, beans and other light\ntruck are materially damaged\nfarmers say.\nCabbage is thought to have\nsurvived the rains better than\nother vegetables. The bright side\nof the crop situation as seen by\nlocal farmers is that in view of\nthe fact that there is little demand\nfor Valley truck, they are saved\nfurther expense with the crop,\nalso, the rains have put a wonder\nful seasoning in the ground for\nthe spring erops Clear skies and\na few davs of drying weather will\nsee the bulk of the citrus crop\nbegin its annual trip to the markets\nof the world.\nSouthern Methodists\nTo Battle Liquor\nEASTLAND. Nov. 14\u2014OP*\u2014South\nerr Methodists, from the individual\ncongregations up. are to be organiz\ned for an educational campaign for\np-ohibitlon and against repeal of\nthe 18th amendment. Dr. A. D. Por\nter. secretary of the central Texas\nMethodist conference and a member\nof the general board of temperance\nand social service of the church,\nsaid here last night.\n\u201cWhen the 18th amendment was\npassed we went to sleep, but now we\nate going to get off the defensive\nand become the aggressors for pro\nhibition.\u2019\u2019 Dr. Porter said. \u201cAnd if\nthe democrats nominate Al. Smith\n;r a man like him. which it looks\nlike they might do. we are going to\nbeat him Mention of Bishop Can\nnon's name was the occasion for\nmild applause.\nOther speakers at the night ses\nsion of the central Texas conference\nwere Mrs. F. P. Culver of Fort\nWorth, who addressed the women,\nand Dr. Cole of Dallas, editor of the\nTexas Christian Advocate.\nDO-X Called\nBOR DEUX. Nov. 14.\u20144s \u2014The\nLe Bourget Airfield today urgently\ncabled the German giant seaplane\nDo-X by wireless, broadcasting\n\u201chave some important meteorol\nogical advice for you.\"\nThe Do-X did not answer and\nhas not signalled since passing\nCherbourg.\nHELLO! GOODBY!\nI U'lo.SiS\nwdod-B><\nflAVHAG00\u00b0&\nA\n--V./>\nLOS ANGELES\u2014Bernice and Mary Ellen Pyle, Los Angeles sisters,\ndo so much traveling to see their parents that they don't see each\nother much. C. G. Pyle, their father, has to spend most of his time\nin Honolulu for business reasons: Mrs. Pyle is compelled by similar\nreasons to live in Los Angeles. So the two daughters commute back\nand forth across the Pacific, on staying with the mother while the\nother stays with the father. At the right in the above picture is\nBernice, snapped as she sailed for Honolulu on the liner Calawaii; at\nthe left is Mary Ellen, shown arriving simultaneously in Los Angeles.\nBaptists Elect Valley Men\nBrownsville, Harlingen and Edinburg Pastor\nPlaced On Executive Board\nAMARILLO, Tex., Nov. 14.\u2014<.4>\u2014So-called 'hard times\" did not prove\nany obstacle to Texas Baptists in their years work, but on th\u00b0 other\nhand not only was the financial \u00aboa! set attained, but $165,517 \u00bbas ap\nplied on the bonded indebtedness.\nTurning from spiritual things to discuss money matters, the Bap ist\nGeneral Convention of Texas, in its final dav's session heard the an\nnual report of the executive board, presented by Dr. W. R. White of\nDallas, secretary\u2019\nNEW BUILDING j\nCONTRACT LET\nContract for a building to house\nPiggly Wiggly Store No. 2 in\nBrownsville to be located on West\nElizabeth Street opposite The Ter\nrace. has been let to R. E. Ewing,\nHarlingen contractor, acccording to\nan annoucement made Friday by j\nH. E. Butt of Harlingen. presiuCin. I\nof Piggly Wiggly-Butt Company,\nInc.\nThe lots on which the building is\nto be located are owned by Mrs.\nJames La Gro of Brownsville, who\nhas closed a five-year lease with\nthe Piggly Wiggly company for the j\ni stor\u20ac space. Cost of the building\nwas not made public.\nThe structure is to be of ule and\nstucco construction, 59x80 feet and\nset back 30 feet from the street in\norder to provide plenty of parking\nspace for customers, said Mr. Bua.\nThis parking space will be concic-\nted so that it will be usable in ah\nI weather.\nIt is hoped to have the building\nready Jan 1. at which time a big\nformal opening will be held.\nThere will be a market in con\nnection with the grocery depart\nment.\nGlenn E. Herman, at present\ncashier at No. 1 store, will be man\nager of the new place. S M. Har\nvev is in charge of Store No. 1 and\nis an experienced man, having been\nin the business in Brownsville eight\nor nine years.\nBrownsville is the first Valley\ntown to have two Piggly Wiggly\nstores Others are located at San\nBenito. Harlingen, Raymondville,\nMercedes. Weslaco, Donna. Pharr.\nEdinburg. McAllen and Mission. The\npresent ownership has been in ef\nfect three years It started with\nthree stores. Another store was de\ncided iyen for grownsville because\nthe business the*\u00a3 demanded it. Mr.\nButt sa!d The new store will have\na more suburban location than the\ndowntown place, and will be more\nconvenient to shoppers from outly*\nmg parts of the city.\n\nRussian Peasants in Revolt\nLONDON. Nov. 14\u2014(.$*>\u2014Fighting\nbetween peasants and communists\nforces resulting in much bloodshed\nin the regions of Ostrov and Optok\nha near the Lettish Russian frontier\nwas reported in Reuters dispatches\nfjom Riga today.\nThe population of a number of\nVillages was reported in the Riga\npieas to have revolted after attempts\nhad been made to enforce the eels\nure of corn and collectivization of\nfat ms.\nThe villages of Jelino and Dublci\nwere said to have been destroyed\nby bombardments from an armored\ntiain while other villages were partly\ndestroyed.\nA number of peasants were report-,\ned to have been executed and many I\nfamilies imprisoned. I\nme oonaea inaemedness of the\nconvention was reduced from\n$1,000,000 as of May 1. 1928. to\n$750,000 at the present time, two\nthirds of the reduction having\nbeen made this year.\nThe budget receipts of the year\namounted to $522,406. but in ad\ndition to this there were many\nother special offerings for objects\nfostered by the State and South\nern Baptist Conventions.\nDr. White said the board had\npursued a policy of paying cash for\nall its current operations and\nmaking reductions on Us indebted\nness.\nTexas Leads World\nDr. W. W. Melton of Waco, chair\nman of the committee on F'ptist\nyoung peoples' unions revealed\nthat Texas with its 4.648 B Y. P.\nU.'s with a combined membership\nof 122.774 led the world in this\nphase of church work.\nThe report of Dr. I E Gates of\nSan Antonio, chairman of the com\nmittee on Evangelism revealed\nthere \u201cwas a favorabIe atmosphere\nin the State for the promotion of\nEvangelism'* the past year.\nThe State Mission Board main\ntained a staff of seven Evangelists\nwho conducted Evangelistic cam\npaigns in many of the more needy\nsections of the slate. Eighty-one\nrevival meetings were held. 2.487\nsermons preached. 3068 persons\nconverted and 2377 baptized and\nadmitted to church membership.\nThe Executive Board was chosen\nas follows:\nExpiring 1931\n(Continued on Page Eight!\nOklahoma Family\nBurned to Death\nMUSKOGEE. Ok!a Nov. 14. M\n\u2014The charred bodies of Bill Ham\nmonds. 45, his wife and their two\nchildren, a boy and a girl, were\nfourvl in the smouldering ruins of\nthe Hammonds farm home near\nCreekola. late last nicht.\nSheriff Fred Hamilton said the\nposition of thf* bodies led him to\nbelieve Harr, londs killed his fain\ntly. set fire to the house and com\nmitted suicide.\nHowever. Jerrv Hammonds bro\nker of the dead man said an exam\nination revealfd the skulls of all of\nhem had been crushed.\nTp*'!or Comttv Vouth\nDies of Grid In\u00bbury\nABILENE. Tex.. Nov. 14\nSuccumbing to injuries suffered\nWednesday durin\u00ae for*ball nractice.\nJoel Darsey. 1\". C^ot\u00abin\nQuarter1''*-b r* fhp hi^h\nfoo^aU t\u201cam ^\u2019ed Iafe\nyesterday His death was the second\nfootball fatality of the season In\nTaylor county. James Johnson,\nstudent in the North Dako'a P\u00ab*-jr\nln V\u00bb\u00bb* f iro K* \u00ab^^e\nhurt in a game wi*h 'me of t\nAbilene school teams Darsey suf\nfered internal injuries\nPORT BOARD\nFILING TIME\nIS PASSED\nThree Commissioners\nCandidates For\nRe-Election\nWith the election of three navig\nation commissioners facing the\nvoters of the districts of the\nBrownsville area, three names have\nbeen filed for re-election to that\nboard.\nThese are John G. Fernandez, Z.\nA. Rosenthal, and John Gregg.\nThis is done in conformity to the\nlegislation requiring that such com\nmissioners be elected by popular\nvote, passed since the appoint\nment of these commissioners some\ntime ago.\nThe election date has been set\nfor December 2, and while it is said\nthat some little opposition has\nbeen heard, mostly expressions of\npersonal individual feeling, it is\ngenerally conceded that a large\nvote Will be piled up for these three\nmen. if voters will remind them\nselves to go to the polls on that\ndav.\nNames for the office are re\nquired to be filled twenty days be\nfore election and it is said the\ntime limit has now expired.\nJohn Gregg is present chairman\nof the board, succeeding Z. A.\nRosenthal when Mr. Rosenthal be\ncame city manager. Others have\nbeen connected with the board in\nthe capacity of employes.\nFor a number of years this body\nhas had before it the great labor\nof the deop water port for Browns\nville How it has worked hand in\nhand with the San Benito and\nPort Isabel districts to pain, chiefly\nthrough John Garner, the ap\npropriation for a Valiev port Is\nnow well known historv in the\nVelley.\nIt was said todav that the pro\ngress of securing the right-of-way\nand lands required by the govern\nment for the Brownsville project\nis prczresing in a most satisfact\nory manne- when the enormous\ndetails of the project are consid\nerd.\nAll three of the men who have\nfiled are candidates to succeed\nthemselves.\nFour Negro* Die\nIn Electric Chair\nLITTLE ROCK. Ark Nov. 14\u2014\n\u2014Four negroes were elctrocuted\nat the state penitentiary early today\nfor two murders committed in rob\nberies last year. They were James\nTurnace and George Washington,\nconvicted of killing W. H. Roberts,\nLittle Rock filling station operator,\nand Eddie Long and Willie Joe Dav\ni is. convict'd of fatally wounding\nJohn Weed. North Little Rock\ngrocery store proprietor and city\nalderman.\nThe executions lasted 32 minutes,\nstarting at 7:13 a. m. and ending at\n7:45 a. m\nUnassisted, the four men walked\nthe few paces separating their cells\ni fr<>m the death chamber and pray\ned in low murmurs. Davis went\nfirst, followed by Long. Turnage and\nWashington.\nHunters Must Pluck\nImported Fowl*\nUnder the new tajiff act. residents\nof the United States hunting in\nMexico are allowed to bring their\ngame back to the United States duty\nfree. Deputy Collector of Customs\nWilliam Neale stated Friday.\nHowever, customs regulations pre\nvent the importation ot feathers\nwhich makes it necessary that hunt\ners pluck their fowds before cross\ning the Rio Grande with them.\nThis new* regulation allowing the\nreturn of wild game duty free Is\nproving popular with American\ni hunters\n\nAssassination Plot\nGENEVA. Nov. 14\u2014 or \u2014The ex\nchange telegraph today said that\nthe Swiss police have been observ\ning great secrecy connection with\na plot discovered yesterday *o as\nsassinate members of the Soviet\ndelegation to the preparatory dis\narmament commission.\n__ _\nATLANTIC AIR LINE\nIS ASSURED AMERICA\n\u2014----U\nHOOVER STARTS RED CROSS DRIVE\na\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u25a0 van\n\u201cI trust that the Red Cross membership drive this year may be more\nsuccessful than ever before. The Red Cross is our national insurance\nagainst the suffering of disaster in any part of our country. It is not\ncharity in the normal sense of gift without obligation Thus\nsaid President Hoover, who is president of the American Red Cro6s,\nat the opening of the annuel membership drive. And here you see\nhim being enrolled by Judge Barton Payne, right, chairman of the\norganization.\ni_\nMiller Pleads Valley Canal\nExtension From Corpus Christi To Border\nUrged By Speaker At New Orleans\nNEW ORLEANS. La Nov. 14oP\u2014Completion of a national inland\nwaterway system in tim\" for the present generation to use it, by the is\nsuance of bonds, if necessary, was advocated by Roy Miller of Corpus\nChristi, acme president of the Intra-Coastal Canal Association, at the\nopening session today of the organization's annual convention here.\nMiller said nation-wide waterway construction program would con\ntribute its part to the relief ol the business depression. He pointed out\ntnat in a statement issued on Julv 3, when the last rivers and harbors\n100 BURIED\nLYONS. France. Nov 14 \u2014,-P\nFear of further land^ides led to\nday to evacuation of a wide area\nabout the section where yesterday\nupwards of 100 persons were buried\nas they slept when their houses\ncollapsed.\nFoundations of the entire district\nare believed to have been under\nmined by extended rains and the\nAntiquailie hospital and even the\nfamous old Cathedral of Sr. Jean\nitself at? threatened. Reinforcing\nof the weakened area is said to be\nimpractical since the undermining\nappears to be too widespread.\nPremen. police and volunteers at\ndawn resumed excavation of the\nruins of the ten or twelve houses\nwhich were caught in the landslides\nfor the bodies of those who were\nburied beneath the tons of masonry.\nOrly five bodies thus have been\nrecovered, and only three of these\nhave been identified Of 15 persons\ntaken alive from the debris sev-\neral are seriously injured and\nprobably will not live\nEstimates on the loss of life\nrange from 50 to 100. with possi\nbility that the real total never will\nbe known. So hamrdous is the\nwork of exca-a?ion that i* mav be\ndavs before manv of the bodies are\nreached\nSt Jean souare today '-ad the\naDoearanre of a ramp, with lone\nrows of armv trucks, ambulances\nand field kitchens arranged to aid\nthe excavation crews\nReds Blamed for Cuban Riot\nTroops Parade Streets of Havana Following\nClashes in Which Six Have Died\nHAVANA, Nov. 14\u2014f.4*i\u2014The mailed fist of the Cuban military was\npoised today above Havana and its environs, prepared to strike hard in\ndefense of the administration of Gerardo Machado, threatened with a\ngrowing island-wide unrest.\nTroops carrying rifles patrolled the city\u2019s streets, with mounted de\ntails here and there. Student assemblies were forbidden and house\nholders remained in their homes.\nA censorship was imposed on all outgoing cable dispatches, and upon\nNow She 11 Be Catty\nLOS ANGELES, Nov. 14.\u2014|\nMitzi, 18-vear-old persian cat, has\ncome into possession of her $15,000\nestate through probation of the\nwill of Mitxi\u2019s late mistress Dr\nMaude F. Cam.\nDr. cair\u00bb died October 18 leaving\na $500,000 estate. By terms of the\nwill Mitzi was bequeathed $15,000\ncash and Dr. Cain's San Gabriel\n.tome -for the purpose of provid\ning upon said premises a home\nand proper care for my cat Mitzi,\nao long as she shall lira-\"\n[ine capita: 5 ucwapapris, ui\nwhich. El Pais and Diano* de la\nMaruia, suspended publication rath\ner than submit to governmental\nsupervision.\nDesultory minor rioting by unor\nganized bands of students lasted\ninto the n;gh:. with one student re\nported dead and a small numbcp\nwounded in clashes yesterday\nAn investigation is being conduc\nted Into the wounding of Arturo\nTagle y Soria, a relative of former\nPresident Mario Menocal. who has\nwo Iced with the Nationalist union\nin opprshicn to the Machado ad\nministration. Tagle. ho is 24 years\nold, and a native of Key West, ria.,\n(Continued on Page Eight)\nbill was approved. President Hoover\ned: \u201cIn aggregate, this in\nland waterway undti taking repre\nsents a larger project than even\nme Panama Canal. It will provide\nemployment for thousands ol men.\nit should be fruitful of decreased\ntransportation charges on bulk\ngoods, should bring great benefits\nto our farms and to our industries.'\nThe great Mississippi river sys\ntem. winch embraces the intra\ncoastal canal, will not be available\nto the American people within the\ndays of the present generation if\npresent methods and policies con\ntinue. the speaker stated.\nTwo Suggestions\nEither annual appropriations\nmust, oe substantially increased ana\np.coabiy uouDied, ot, n that is not\nieasibie, the project must oe t.\nnanced in its entirety by bond is\nsue and tne work placed under con\ntinuing contracts so that comple\ntion may be reaiued within a reas\nonable time.\n\u201cWhen it is considered that ap\nproximately $18,000 must be al\nloted each year for maintenance of\nexisting projects, leaving only a\nlittle more than $30.0tl\u2019,000 annual\nly for actual construction, the ut\nter inadequacy of the past policy\nof $50,000,000 annual appropria\ntion is at once apparent.\u201d He add\ned it appeared that an annual ap\npropriation of 8100.000,000 consti\ntuted the \u201cirreducible minimum.\u201d\n\u201cUnder ordinary circumstances a\npav-as-ycu-go pogrom undoubt\nedly constitutes .sound economic\npolicy. Such a proRram, however,\ncan only be projected and carded\nout upon the basis of adequate\ncurrent revenues.\nReserve Fund Use Urged\nJust now we are in a position\nnationally where income both to\nthe individual and to the govern\nment has been curtailed. Notwith\nstanding that fact, we have amass\ned tremendous reserves in national\nwealth.\n\u201cIf our curtailed income will not\npermit us to do this tremendous\njob of completing our national in\nland waterway system on a pav\nas-vou-RO basis, is it not perfectly\nsound that we should utilize some\nof the reserves in a financing pro\ngram in order that we mav not\nonly stimulate present condition!\nbut also guarantee our country'!\nfuture progress?\u201d\nGood Progress\n\nThe speaker pointed out thai\n\"splendid progress naci been mau\u00ab\non the mtra-coastal canal, wmer\nis authorized for 600 miles frotr\nthe Mississippi river west and soutt\n1 through the coastal sections oi\nLouisiana and Texas to Corpui\niChristi. \"Ten dredges are now' a\nwork in Southern Louisiana ant\na completed waterway with a nine\nfoot depth and 100 foot bo'.torr\nwidth, via the Pbquemine routi\nfrom Morgan City to the jabtn<\ndistrict in Texas, is anticipatec\nwithin two years. In Texts, al\nrights cf .ay covering the sectloc\nfrom the Sabine district to Gal\n(Continued on Page Eight)\nMAIL SERVICE\nTO BE OPENED\nWITHIN YEAR\nPanamerican Airways\nAnd English Co.\nTo Operate\nWASHINGTON. Nov. 14-h/P>\u2014\nPlans for an Anglo-American air\nnail line across the Atlantic today\nwere said by W. Irving Glover, sec\nond assist an* postmaster general to\nbe settled.\nPan American Airways. Inc and\nImperial Airways. Ltd., of England,\nwill operate the line, which has been\nplanned to bejin within another\nyear.\" Glover said.\n\"Everything has been settled with\nthe exception of equipment, spread\ning of weather facilities, and loca\ntion of landing fields both in the\nStates and other points.\n\"The postoffice department, which\nhas been aware of negotiations be\ntween the two companies for some\ntime is prepared to give mail to the\nline, whenever it is ready.\"\nHe said Charleston. S. C., may be\nthe American terminus of the line\nbecause of its location below the\nbad weather belt. s.\n_\nLittle Light Thrown\nOn Man Found Dead\nEfforts to identify the\nfound m the Arroyo Coloiauo\nWednesday as that of Paul du.,\nHouston prombitiun agent m^uig\nsince June, had met with no suc\ncess fritiay.\nThe bony was caught in the Ar\nroyo about a mile south ot tne\nrailroad bndge by fishermen Wed\nnesday.\nClaude C. Towers, pressman at\nihe Bishop Print shop, saiu tne\nbody might be that of his brother\nin-law, Paul Beck, who has been\nmissing. Towers said the descrip\ntion litted his brother-in-law.\nBeck was last seen near Shreve\nport in June while on duty as a\nprohibition agent. Towers wired\nlelatives Thursday to determine\nwhether Beck had been located out\nhad received no answer at noon.\nThe body was brought here Wed\nnesday and decomposition had set\nin so badly that it wras buried im\nmediately by the Marcelo Garza\nundertaking establishment.\nA. L. Pickens of Edinburg Thu s\nday said the body might be that\nof Will Brummitt who disappear\ned from Portia. Ark.. Oct. 22. No\ncheck had been made in this ease\nup to noon.\nRegistration Night\nb or Touristst Opens\nTo aul tourists to better eiijoy\ntheir visit to Brownsville, ana to\nhelp new residents get acquainted\nwitn each other, each Thursday\nevening lias been devoted to wout\nwil be Known as Registration Night\nat the tourist room of the local\nchamber of commerce, according\nto Mrs. Ralph A. Warden, hostess.\nThe first Registration evening is\nscheduled for Tuesday, Nov. 18, at\n7:30, and all tourists, visitors and\nthose residents who have moved\nhere within the past year are in\nvited to be present.\n\u201cYou would be surprised at the\nnumber of winter tourists In\nBrownsville at present.\u201d Mrs. War\nden said Friday morning \"And\nthe number of new families, es\npecially in the El Jardin district,\nis amazing. We vant to make the\ntourists visit here as pleasant as\npossible, and when they leave we\nwant them to carry away with\nthem a good impression of Browns\nville and the Valley.\u201d\nPLAITNIFF WINS\nA judgment for the plaintiff\nwas returned in the Cameron\ncounty court at law Friday morn\ning in the case of Texas Develop\nment, Inc., vs P. W. Perkins, et al.\nThe case was a suit on contract.\ni WEATHER j\nFor Brownsville and the Valley:\nCloudy to partly cloudy tonight and\nSaturday; not much change in tem\nperature.\nFor East Texas: Cloudy tonight\nand Saturday with occasional rains;\ncooler in northwest portion. Satur\nday.\nModerate to fresh southerly winds\non the coast.\nRIVER FORECAST\nThere will be no mateiial change\nin the river during the next 24 to\n48 hours.\nFlood Pmeat 24-Hr. 24-Hr.\nStage Stage Chant Halo\nEagle P